<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
As some of you may know, I work in real estate. I need to complain for a couple of minutes about these people who are suing Dominion Homes <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
We live in a Dominion Home that was just completed in December out here between Westerville and New Albany. We couldn't be happier with them and with the quality of our house. What ticks me off about these people who have been in our major newspaper repeatedly is that they can't expect a homebuilder to do their &quot;homework&quot; for them. We had to sit down and figure out whether or not we could afford our house before signing the contract. Dominion layed out in great detail what our options were and ALL of the things we should take into consideration. My wife and I are big on information, especially me, when making a decision. It took us six months to finally decide to buy through Dominion. We looked at every builder in town and they came out on top. I would HIGHLY recommend them to anyone. 
<br />

<br />
No house is guranteed to rise in value. Maybe our house won't raise in value but to the best of my knowledge we have the potential to make a nice profit off this place. Just like when buying stocks you figure out your potential for return on your investment and if it's to your liking you buy the stock. Unfortunately the value of that stock or in this case house may NOT rise in value...it may actually decline even though its virtually new. The location, quality of schools, and other things unrelated to your home itself determines it's value. The amount you pay in taxes is based on an ESTIMATE of the value of your home, which in most cases is actually less than what you could sell it for. Also, the market plays a part in determining the value of your house. Right now here in central Ohio there is no housing shortage like there was in the 50's and 60's. We are selling record numbers of homes but the inventory of available homes has also increased substantially in the past 3 years. The economy in our area has slowed from where it was in the 90's so we're not growing as fast as we were. The trendy areas like German and Victorian Village aren't even selling as well as they had been probably due to overinflated prices for the existing market. 
<br />

<br />
My top 5 list of imporant &quot;homework&quot; to do when buying a house:
<br />

<br />
1. Quality of Schools...this one his HUGE. You may not have any kids but if you want the value of your house to die FAST vote against school levies. A lot of people are considering moves out of Westerville right now because of the amount of cutbacks they've made the past few years. 
<br />

<br />
2. What is in the area...a landfill or industrial areas will really hurt the re-sale value of your house. You want to be especially careful of this when building a house. The cost of building is based on materials and labor not re-sale value. You better not build a new house in Obetz and expect a huge return on your investment. It doesn't happen down there. Another poor re-sale area is the Southwest side of Columbus.
<br />

<br />
3. What am I building this house for? Am I going to be here long-term or short term. If you're not going to be there long you'd better build somewhere that is &quot;in-demand&quot; right now because it's not likely to go out of demand in less than 5 years. It sometimes takes people a while to figure out when something is &quot;out of style&quot; you see them all the time sporting bad mullets or leather pants <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
4. What do I want to pay....NOT what can I afford because you can always qualify for a lot more loan than you should want. Look at how much you want to have tied up in house payments. Don't forget that you're going to need money for the bills and upkeep associated with a house (even if it's new).
<br />

<br />
5. Taxes, Don't forget when building a house that real estate taxes are paid &quot;in arrears&quot; which means you pay it after you actually owe it. When you build a house you're only paying real estate taxes on vacant land the first year you're there. If you pay your taxes as part of your house payment make it so that you're payment is based on what the estimate of taxes on both the house and land together will be so you don't get a big surprise year 2 (of a $500+ rise in your house payment). The money goes into an escrow account so you'll have a surplus your first year if you do this. You won't lose the money.
<br />

<br />
Finally, in conclusion...if you screw up and your house doesn't rise in value don't blame the builder, take it on the chin and do a better job next time. These people are smart enough to figure out how to file a lawsuit yet not smart enough to get help in figuring out buying a house...good grief <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Take a buyers' agent with you. They can help you and most builders will pay their commission. It costs you NOTHING.</td>
