<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
I'll throw in my two cents...
<br />

<br />
When buying a house, get the &quot;Keep up with the Joneses&quot; mentality out of your head... especially your first home.  We bought our first house after three years of apartment living.  I know we drove the realtor nuts, cuz he musta showed us 30-40 homes.
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, we found a nice starter home that was only 9 years old.  Good neighborhood, and we kept our payment at a very reasonable amount.  All that to make this point... we've been able to furnish and do renovations without racking up a bunch of debt cuz we don't have an outrageous house payment.  I have friends who literally have nothing but a card table and chairs in their gorgeous, expensive homes that they probably bought way too early.  N-A makes a great point...  most lenders will tell you that you can afford a lot more house.  They don't tell you that you have to live on Mac-n-cheese until you pay the thing down.  My wife and I worked out our budget and decided we could comfortably afford $xxx a month for a house payment.  We sat down with our realtor and said here's what we can pay, tell us how much house we can buy.
<br />

<br />
It didn't hurt that we found a house that had been a HUD repo...  I can do a lot of handy-work, so I've done a lot of renovations to the house and built our equity up very quickly.
<br />

<br />
Do your homework and have a plan!  Our plan is to live here for another three years, get the equity up.  Hopefully we'll buy a few acres of land and then build on it.</td>
